The main idea for fluid flow simulation is the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations. The equations are ∂⃗u/∂t + u  · ∇⃗u + 1/ρ ∇p = g  + ν∇ · ∇⃗u and ∇ · u  = 0.

u is the velocity of the fluid. The greek letter ρ is for the density. The normal p is for pressure, which is the force per unit area that the fluid exerts on anything. g is just gravity, as well as any additional control accelerations that might be wanted on top of gravity. These are also called body forces. The Greek letter ν is the kinematic viscosity. The first equation is the momentum equation, and really is just F = ma. The second one is the incompressibility condition.

	We need to find the net forces acting on a particle. To do that we find the negative gradient of pressure, -∇⃗p and multiply by volume V. The other fluid force is due to viscosity, which is a force that makes a particle move at the same speed as the nearby particles. We can use the Laplacian, which is a differential operator that measures how far a quantity is from the average around it. Using that and integrating over the volume, as well as the dynamic viscosity coefficient, μ. Then the F = ma equation becomes m D⃗ u/Dt = m⃗ g − V ∇p + V μ∇ · ∇⃗u. This is just for individual particles, so we take the limit as the number of particles goes to infinity  and the size goes to zero. First we divide by V so we get something meaningful, and m/V = density, ρ. Taking the limit and rearranging you get D⃗ uDt + (1/ρ) ∇p =⃗ g + (μ/ρ) ∇ · ∇⃗u
